<h1>@HI{{tame ni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li>@Vru{{}}(<em>volitional</em>) <strong>@HI{{tame ni}}</strong>, <em>volitional expression</em>
<li>@N{{}} @HI{{no}} <strong>@HI{{tame ni}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

These sentence patterns indicate a purpose. The pattern @N{{}} @HI{{no <strong>tame ni</strong>}} can also indicate
"for the benefit of @N{{}}".
</br>>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{oneself}}@KJ{{part}}@HI{{no}}@KJ{{store}}@HI{{wo}}@KJ{{hold}}@HI{{tsu}} <strong>@HI{{tame ni}}</strong>,
      @KJ{{savings}}@KJ{{gold}}@HI{{shite imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I am saving money in order to have my own shop.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{house}}@KJ{{tribe}}@HI{{no}}<strong>@HI{{tame ni}}</strong>, @HI{{uchi wo}}@KJ{{build}}@HI{{temasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I will build a house for my family.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

The similar expression @HI{{you ni}} is used in clauses with verbs that do not contain volition,
whereas <strong>@HI{{tame ni}}</strong> is used with verbs that do. Note that if the verb involved
is @HI{{naru}}, then whether or not volition is invovled depends on the sentence.
</br>

